1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,839
After May 9, in the housing market,

2
00:00:04,839 --> 00:00:07,258
it won't be about home prices so much as

3
00:00:07,258 --> 00:00:11,794
which signals

4
00:00:11,794 --> 00:00:13,911
show up first.

5
00:00:13,911 --> 00:00:17,540
That's what a lot of people are asking.

6
00:00:17,540 --> 00:00:21,774
Will home prices start rising again now?

7
00:00:21,774 --> 00:00:26,613
Or will they bounce briefly and turn back down?

8
00:00:26,613 --> 00:00:29,940
But the market right now

9
00:00:29,940 --> 00:00:33,871
keeps proving you wrong

10
00:00:33,871 --> 00:00:36,290
if you look at it

11
00:00:36,290 --> 00:00:39,314
in just one direction.

12
00:00:39,314 --> 00:00:41,431
The reason is simple.

13
00:00:41,431 --> 00:00:45,665
Right now, the country as a whole

14
00:00:45,665 --> 00:00:47,177
is not moving

15
00:00:47,177 --> 00:00:56,553
in a single cycle.

16
00:00:56,553 --> 00:00:58,972
Interest rates, regulations, lending, and sentiment

17
00:00:58,972 --> 00:01:01,996
are all working differently

18
00:01:01,996 --> 00:01:04,113
from one region to another.

19
00:01:04,113 --> 00:01:07,137
So today,

20
00:01:07,137 --> 00:01:10,766
instead of asking whether prices will rise or fall,

21
00:01:10,766 --> 00:01:12,580
we're going to look at

22
00:01:12,580 --> 00:01:14,697
where the market will split first.

23
00:01:14,697 --> 00:01:16,511
First,

24
00:01:16,511 --> 00:01:18,628
let's start with the backdrop.

25
00:01:18,628 --> 00:01:21,955
Right now, interest rates

26
00:01:21,955 --> 00:01:23,467
do not look like

27
00:01:23,467 --> 00:01:28,003
they're about to fall sharply.

28
00:01:28,003 --> 00:01:31,330
When rates stay on hold,

29
00:01:31,330 --> 00:01:32,842
it means two things

30
00:01:32,842 --> 00:01:36,471
for the market.

31
00:01:36,471 --> 00:01:39,495
Borrowing costs

32
00:01:39,495 --> 00:01:42,822
are not getting worse

33
00:01:42,822 --> 00:01:44,939
all that quickly.

34
00:01:44,939 --> 00:01:49,173
But at the same time,

35
00:01:49,173 --> 00:01:50,685
financial conditions are not improving enough

36
00:01:50,685 --> 00:01:53,407
to push buying demand

37
00:01:53,407 --> 00:01:58,548
that much either.

38
00:01:58,548 --> 00:02:01,572
That's the key point.

39
00:02:01,572 --> 00:02:03,689
If lending conditions don't loosen meaningfully,

40
00:02:03,689 --> 00:02:07,016
regional gaps

41
00:02:07,016 --> 00:02:08,528
only get wider.

42
00:02:08,528 --> 00:02:12,157
Places supported by real end-user demand

43
00:02:12,157 --> 00:02:14,879
will hold up.

44
00:02:14,879 --> 00:02:19,113
Places with weak investor demand

45
00:02:19,113 --> 00:02:21,835
will stay under more pressure.

46
00:02:21,835 --> 00:02:24,859
This is where

47
00:02:24,859 --> 00:02:27,883
the regulatory factor

48
00:02:27,883 --> 00:02:30,907
also matters a great deal.

49
00:02:30,907 --> 00:02:33,931
Real estate doesn't move

50
00:02:33,931 --> 00:02:36,653
on interest rates alone.

51
00:02:36,653 --> 00:02:38,467
Lending rules, taxes,

52
00:02:38,467 --> 00:02:40,281
and policy messaging

53
00:02:40,281 --> 00:02:44,212
can immediately change

54
00:02:44,212 --> 00:02:47,841
the market's temperature.

55
00:02:47,841 --> 00:02:51,168
If the market

56
00:02:51,168 --> 00:02:54,797
reads it as deregulation,

57
00:02:54,797 --> 00:02:58,426
expectations

58
00:02:58,426 --> 00:03:00,543
can react before prices do.

59
00:03:00,543 --> 00:03:04,172
On the other hand, if household debt controls

60
00:03:04,172 --> 00:03:08,103
and tighter lending restrictions

61
00:03:08,103 --> 00:03:09,615
are emphasized,

62
00:03:09,615 --> 00:03:12,639
transaction activity

63
00:03:12,639 --> 00:03:17,175
could shrink again first.

64
00:03:17,175 --> 00:03:20,804
So when looking

65
00:03:20,804 --> 00:03:22,316
at the period after May 9,

66
00:03:22,316 --> 00:03:23,828
before you look at price numbers,

67
00:03:23,828 --> 00:03:27,759
you need to read

68
00:03:27,759 --> 00:03:30,178
the policy signals first.

69
00:03:30,178 --> 00:03:31,992
Is the message being sent to the market

70
00:03:31,992 --> 00:03:34,411
easing,

71
00:03:34,411 --> 00:03:36,830
or restraint?

72
00:03:36,830 --> 00:03:40,761
That difference is enormous.

73
00:03:40,761 --> 00:03:44,390
Now let's look

74
00:03:44,390 --> 00:03:46,507
at the scenarios.

75
00:03:46,507 --> 00:03:51,043
First,

76
00:03:51,043 --> 00:03:55,277
rates have paused,

77
00:03:55,277 --> 00:03:57,394
and regulatory pressure is limited.

78
00:03:57,394 --> 00:04:02,233
In that case, the most desirable areas

79
00:04:02,233 --> 00:04:04,652
and prime locations

80
00:04:04,652 --> 00:04:07,374
could see transactions recover first.

81
00:04:07,374 --> 00:04:10,096
Even if prices don't jump sharply,

82
00:04:10,096 --> 00:04:13,725
they may stabilize first

83
00:04:13,725 --> 00:04:17,656
or edge up modestly.

84
00:04:17,656 --> 00:04:21,890
Second,

85
00:04:21,890 --> 00:04:24,309
rates have paused,

86
00:04:24,309 --> 00:04:28,240
but regulations tighten

87
00:04:28,240 --> 00:04:30,357
or the lending bar gets higher.

88
00:04:30,357 --> 00:04:32,474
Then buyers waiting on the sidelines

89
00:04:32,474 --> 00:04:34,893
shift back into wait-and-see mode.

90
00:04:34,893 --> 00:04:38,824
At that point, more than prices,

91
00:04:38,824 --> 00:04:42,151
transaction volume

92
00:04:42,151 --> 00:04:46,082
cools off first.

93
00:04:46,082 --> 00:04:49,711
The market

94
00:04:49,711 --> 00:04:51,223
starts to feel quiet.

95
00:04:51,223 --> 00:04:55,759
Third,

96
00:04:55,759 --> 00:04:59,086
the national average stays muted.

97
00:04:59,086 --> 00:05:03,017
But Seoul's core districts

98
00:05:03,017 --> 00:05:07,251
and some parts of the metro area stay strong.

99
00:05:07,251 --> 00:05:10,275
By contrast, provincial areas and outer suburbs

100
00:05:10,275 --> 00:05:13,602
remain weak.

101
00:05:13,602 --> 00:05:17,231
That means

102
00:05:17,231 --> 00:05:19,650
a fully bifurcated market

103
00:05:19,650 --> 00:05:21,767
continues.

104
00:05:21,767 --> 00:05:24,489
Right now, I think

105
00:05:24,489 --> 00:05:29,025
this third scenario

106
00:05:29,025 --> 00:05:31,747
is the most realistic.

107
00:05:31,747 --> 00:05:35,678
We've already seen

108
00:05:35,678 --> 00:05:36,887
similar patterns

109
00:05:36,887 --> 00:05:40,516
many times.

110
00:05:40,516 --> 00:05:44,447
Even under the same rate environment,

111
00:05:44,447 --> 00:05:46,866
places backed by jobs

112
00:05:46,866 --> 00:05:50,193
and strong school districts

113
00:05:50,193 --> 00:05:53,520
tend to attract

114
00:05:53,520 --> 00:05:55,939
transactions.

115
00:05:55,939 --> 00:05:58,661
Places with expectations of better transit

116
00:05:58,661 --> 00:06:00,173
also react first.

117
00:06:00,173 --> 00:06:02,592
By contrast, places facing

118
00:06:02,592 --> 00:06:05,919
a heavy wave of new supply.

119
00:06:05,919 --> 00:06:07,431
Places with weak demand fundamentals.

120
00:06:07,431 --> 00:06:09,245
These areas recover

121
00:06:09,245 --> 00:06:12,269
much more slowly.

122
00:06:12,269 --> 00:06:15,293
In the end, the economy

123
00:06:15,293 --> 00:06:18,620
and real estate do not move separately.

124
00:06:18,620 --> 00:06:21,644
Just because rates have paused

125
00:06:21,644 --> 00:06:24,668
doesn't mean prices

126
00:06:24,668 --> 00:06:27,390
immediately go up.

127
00:06:27,390 --> 00:06:29,507
And just because new regulations appear

128
00:06:29,507 --> 00:06:32,229
doesn't mean the market

129
00:06:32,229 --> 00:06:36,463
automatically crashes.

130
00:06:36,463 --> 00:06:39,487
The real market

131
00:06:39,487 --> 00:06:42,209
is far more complex.

132
00:06:42,209 --> 00:06:44,628
Income conditions,

133
00:06:44,628 --> 00:06:49,769
borrowing capacity,

134
00:06:49,769 --> 00:06:52,793
local demand,

135
00:06:52,793 --> 00:06:56,120
and policy interpretation

136
00:06:56,120 --> 00:06:57,632
all move together.

137
00:06:57,632 --> 00:06:59,446
So right now,

138
00:06:59,446 --> 00:07:03,982
more than a one-line forecast,

139
00:07:03,982 --> 00:07:09,426
it's much more important

140
00:07:09,426 --> 00:07:11,845
to see which scenario

141
00:07:11,845 --> 00:07:13,962
your area falls into.

142
00:07:13,962 --> 00:07:19,103
To sum up,

143
00:07:19,103 --> 00:07:23,034
the key to home prices after May 9

144
00:07:23,034 --> 00:07:26,663
is not

145
00:07:26,663 --> 00:07:29,082
answering in one word

146
00:07:29,082 --> 00:07:32,106
whether they'll rise or fall.

147
00:07:32,106 --> 00:07:35,433
A rate pause

148
00:07:35,433 --> 00:07:38,760
can help support the floor.

149
00:07:38,760 --> 00:07:41,784
But depending on regulation and lending signals,

150
00:07:41,784 --> 00:07:46,320
some areas may recover

151
00:07:46,320 --> 00:07:49,647
while others

152
00:07:49,647 --> 00:07:52,671
get held back more clearly.

153
00:07:52,671 --> 00:07:56,905
What will matter even more going forward

154
00:07:56,905 --> 00:07:59,929
is not the average price.
